We see you, sister.

00:55:41.109 --> 00:55:45.321 line:90% position:50% align:center
Dear sisters, you are wonderful examples.

00:55:45.321 --> 00:55:48.366 line:90% position:50% align:center
We appreciate all that you do.

00:55:48.366 --> 00:55:50.785 line:90% position:50% align:center
We love you dearly.

00:55:51.577 --> 00:55:53.996 line:90% position:50% align:center
In this month’s program,

00:55:53.996 --> 00:55:57.500 line:90% position:50% align:center
we were encouraged
to imitate Jehovah’s generosity

00:55:57.500 --> 00:56:00.753 line:90% position:50% align:center
by showing hospitality,

00:56:00.753 --> 00:56:03.673 line:90% position:50% align:center
we uncovered a valuable lesson

00:56:03.673 --> 00:56:07.427 line:90% position:50% align:center
about loyal love in the book of Hosea,

00:56:07.427 --> 00:56:09.929 line:90% position:50% align:center
and we were reminded

00:56:09.929 --> 00:56:14.392 line:90% position:50% align:center
that the hard work parents
put into training their children

00:56:14.392 --> 00:56:18.813 line:90% position:50% align:center
produces strong faith and a sure hope.

00:56:18.813 --> 00:56:21.441 line:90% position:50% align:center
For this month’s postcard,

00:56:21.441 --> 00:56:24.444 line:90% position:50% align:center
we travel to French Guiana

00:56:24.444 --> 00:56:26.529 line:90% position:50% align:center
in South America.

00:56:27.321 --> 00:56:31.200 line:90% position:50% align:center
This is a lush, tropical land.

00:56:31.200 --> 00:56:35.371 line:90% position:50% align:center
Well over 90 percent of French Guiana
is covered in forests

00:56:35.371 --> 00:56:39.584 line:90% position:50% align:center
fed by heavy rains from December to July.

00:56:40.334 --> 00:56:43.254 line:90% position:50% align:center
An extraordinary variety of plants,

00:56:44.005 --> 00:56:47.008 line:90% position:50% align:center
mammals, birds,

00:56:48.009 --> 00:56:50.011 line:90% position:50% align:center
and insects thrive here.

00:56:50.845 --> 00:56:54.515 line:90% position:50% align:center
Beautiful diversity
is also seen in the people

00:56:54.515 --> 00:56:56.517 line:90% position:50% align:center
and the many cultures,

00:56:56.517 --> 00:56:59.687 line:90% position:50% align:center
among them Creole, French,

00:56:59.687 --> 00:57:03.774 line:90% position:50% align:center
Surinamese, Brazilian, and South Asian.

00:57:04.692 --> 00:57:07.570 line:90% position:50% align:center
This land became a French colony

00:57:07.570 --> 00:57:10.198 line:90% position:50% align:center
in the 17th century.

00:57:10.198 --> 00:57:13.618 line:90% position:50% align:center
For decades, thousands of convicts

00:57:13.618 --> 00:57:15.912 line:90% position:50% align:center
were sentenced to forced labor

00:57:15.912 --> 00:57:18.414 line:90% position:50% align:center
in places like Royale Island,

00:57:18.414 --> 00:57:20.666 line:90% position:50% align:center
Devil’s Island, and Kourou.

00:57:21.876 --> 00:57:25.630 line:90% position:50% align:center
Happily, those things are in the past.

00:57:25.630 --> 00:57:29.675 line:90% position:50% align:center
Today, French Guiana remains
part of the French Republic,

00:57:29.675 --> 00:57:34.222 line:90% position:50% align:center
though it’s more than
4,000 miles (6,000 km) from France.

00:57:34.222 --> 00:57:36.224 line:90% position:50% align:center
Kourou is now the site

00:57:36.224 --> 00:57:40.061 line:90% position:50% align:center
of a European Space Agency Center.

00:57:41.145 --> 00:57:42.563 line:90% position:50% align:center
The Kingdom message

00:57:42.563 --> 00:57:45.024 line:90% position:50% align:center
first reached French Guiana

00:57:45.024 --> 00:57:47.652 line:90% position:50% align:center
when Brother Olga Laaland,

00:57:47.652 --> 00:57:50.655 line:90% position:50% align:center
a zealous minister from Guadeloupe,

00:57:50.655 --> 00:57:53.407 line:90% position:50% align:center
arrived in 1945.

00:57:53.407 --> 00:57:55.409 line:90% position:50% align:center
Over the next two years,

00:57:55.409 --> 00:57:58.538 line:90% position:50% align:center
he joyfully shared the good news in villages,

00:57:58.538 --> 00:58:01.999 line:90% position:50% align:center
gold mines, and trading posts.

00:58:01.999 --> 00:58:04.627 line:90% position:50% align:center
Though his stay was temporary,

00:58:04.627 --> 00:58:07.171 line:90% position:50% align:center
he planted many seeds of truth.

00:58:08.089 --> 00:58:10.508 line:90% position:50% align:center
Xavier and Sara Noll,

00:58:10.508 --> 00:58:14.428 line:90% position:50% align:center
after graduating from Gilead in 1958,

00:58:14.428 --> 00:58:16.430 line:90% position:50% align:center
went to help a small group

00:58:16.430 --> 00:58:19.433 line:90% position:50% align:center
in the capital city, Cayenne,

00:58:19.433 --> 00:58:23.646 line:90% position:50% align:center
which is said to be
the birthplace of cayenne pepper.

00:58:25.439 --> 00:58:29.360 line:90% position:50% align:center
Soon Brother Noll
was conducting daily Bible studies

00:58:29.360 --> 00:58:31.696 line:90% position:50% align:center
with Christian Bonecaze.

00:58:33.406 --> 00:58:35.825 line:90% position:50% align:center
Within a short time,

00:58:35.825 --> 00:58:37.827 line:90% position:50% align:center
Christian and his friends

00:58:37.827 --> 00:58:41.706 line:90% position:50% align:center
became the first baptized Witnesses
in French Guiana.

00:58:44.292 --> 00:58:47.545 line:90% position:50% align:center
Today, an average of 3,000 publishers

00:58:47.545 --> 00:58:49.964 line:90% position:50% align:center
proclaim the good news.

00:58:49.964 --> 00:58:53.509 line:90% position:50% align:center
Recently two milestones were reached:

00:58:53.509 --> 00:58:56.888 line:90% position:50% align:center
a peak of 700 regular pioneers

00:58:56.888 --> 00:58:59.765 line:90% position:50% align:center
and a record Memorial attendance

00:58:59.765 --> 00:59:03.019 line:90% position:50% align:center
of more than 11,500

00:59:03.019 --> 00:59:06.856 line:90% position:50% align:center
—nearly four times the number of publishers.

00:59:07.815 --> 00:59:10.234 line:90% position:50% align:center
Although most of the population

00:59:10.234 --> 00:59:13.988 line:90% position:50% align:center
is concentrated in and around Cayenne,

00:59:13.988 --> 00:59:16.198 line:90% position:50% align:center
our brothers work hard

00:59:16.198 --> 00:59:19.160 line:90% position:50% align:center
to find people everywhere.

00:59:19.160 --> 00:59:21.162 line:90% position:50% align:center
This isn’t easy.

00:59:21.162 --> 00:59:25.249 line:90% position:50% align:center
Only 40 percent
of the country’s roads are paved.

00:59:25.249 --> 00:59:28.836 line:90% position:50% align:center
Some rivers have treacherous rapids,

00:59:28.836 --> 00:59:31.923 line:90% position:50% align:center
bearing names like Saut Fracas,

00:59:31.923 --> 00:59:34.634 line:90% position:50% align:center
or Crash Rapids,

00:59:34.634 --> 00:59:37.053 line:90% position:50% align:center
and A Dieu Vať,

00:59:37.053 --> 00:59:41.474 line:90% position:50% align:center
which translates into “That’s the End of It.”

00:59:41.474 --> 00:59:45.186 line:90% position:50% align:center
Undaunted, publishers travel by boat

00:59:45.186 --> 00:59:48.940 line:90% position:50% align:center
to reach people in distant territories.

00:59:48.940 --> 00:59:51.859 line:90% position:50% align:center
Preaching is done in many languages,

00:59:51.859 --> 00:59:56.530 line:90% position:50% align:center
including Palikur, Tyrewuju, and Hmong.

00:59:57.657 --> 01:00:02.203 line:90% position:50% align:center
Three congregations serve the needs
of those who speak Saramaccan.

01:00:02.870 --> 01:00:07.208 line:90% position:50% align:center
Seven congregations
and a remote translation office

01:00:07.208 --> 01:00:11.045 line:90% position:50% align:center
support the French Guianese Creole field.

01:00:12.380 --> 01:00:15.633 line:90% position:50% align:center
When our brothers gather for association,

01:00:15.633 --> 01:00:20.304 line:90% position:50% align:center
they enjoy dancing,
singing, and playing music.

01:00:21.222 --> 01:00:24.809 line:90% position:50% align:center
A famous local dish
called <i>bouillon d’awara </i>

01:00:24.809 --> 01:00:27.269 line:90% position:50% align:center
can often be found on the table.

01:00:27.269 --> 01:00:31.524 line:90% position:50% align:center
This is a stew
made of the pulp of awara fruit

01:00:31.524 --> 01:00:34.652 line:90% position:50% align:center
and is typically mixed with smoked meats

01:00:34.652 --> 01:00:36.696 line:90% position:50% align:center
and fresh seafood.

01:00:36.696 --> 01:00:39.532 line:90% position:50% align:center
As we depart French Guiana,

01:00:39.532 --> 01:00:43.202 line:90% position:50% align:center
we receive warm greetings
from our brothers and sisters

01:00:43.202 --> 01:00:47.665 line:90% position:50% align:center
who meet at the Saint-Laurent
du Maroni Kingdom Hall

01:00:47.665 --> 01:00:51.669 line:90% position:50% align:center
and from the remote translation office
in Cayenne.

01:00:55.131 --> 01:00:57.883 line:90% position:50% align:center
They say to us, <i>“Nou kontan zot!” </i>

01:00:57.883 --> 01:00:59.510 line:90% position:50% align:center
“We love you!”

01:00:59.510 --> 01:01:04.515 line:90% position:50% align:center
From the World Headquarters
of Jehovah’s Witnesses,

01:01:04.515 --> 01:01:08.561 line:90% position:50% align:center
this is JW Broadcasting!

